<div id=3D"What-is-an-Arithmetic-Sequence">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>What is an Arithmetic Sequence?</h2>
</div>
<p>An <strong>arithmetic sequence </strong>is defined in two ways. It is a =
"sequence where the differences between every two successive terms are the =
same" (or) In an arithmetic sequence, "every term is obtained by adding a f=
ixed number (positive or negative or zero) to its previous term". The follo=
wing is an arithmetic sequence as every term is obtained by adding a fixed =
number 4 to its previous term.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"arithmetic sequence" src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt9iqe.cloudfron=
t.net/media/seo_landing_files/definition-and-example-of-arithmetic-sequence=
-definition-and-example-of-arithmetic-sequence-1633103178.png" style=3D"wid=
th: 400px;"></p>
<h3>Arithmetic Sequence Example</h3>
<p>Consider the sequence 3, 6, 9, 12, 15, .... is an arithmetic sequence be=
cause every term is obtained by <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/numbers/=
addition/">adding</a> a constant number (3) to its previous term.</p>
<p>Here,</p>
<ul>
<li>The first term, a =3D 3</li>
<li>The common difference, d =3D 6 - 3 =3D 9 - 6 =3D 12 - 9 =3D 15 - 12 =3D=
 ... =3D 3</li>
</ul>
<p>Thus, an arithmetic sequence can be written as a, a + d, a + 2d, a + 3d,=
 .... Let us verify this pattern for the above example.</p>
<p>a, a + d, a + 2d, a + 3d, a + 4d, ... =3D 3, 3 + 3, 3 + 2(3), 3 + 3(3), =
3 + 4(3),... =3D 3, 6, 9, 12,15,....</p>
<p>A few more examples of an arithmetic sequence are:</p>
<ul>
<li>5, 8, 11, 14, ...</li>
<li>80, 75, 70, 65, 60, ...</li>
<li>=CF=80/2, =CF=80, 3=CF=80/2, 2=CF=80, ....</li>
<li>-=E2=88=9A2, -2=E2=88=9A2, -3=E2=88=9A2, -4=E2=88=9A2, ...</li>
</ul>
<div id=3D"Arithmetic-Sequence-Formula">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Arithmetic Sequence Formula</h2>
</div>
<p>The first term of an arithmetic sequence is a, its common difference is =
d, n is the number of terms. The general form of the AP is a, a+d, a+2d, a+=
3d,......up to n terms. We have different <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.co=
m/arithmetic-sequence-formula/">formulas</a> associated with an arithmetic =
sequence used to calculate the n<sup>th</sup> term, the sum of n terms of a=
n AP, or the common difference of a given arithmetic sequence.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Arithmetic Sequence Formula" src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt9iqe.c=
loudfront.net/media/seo_landing_files/formulas-of-arithmetic-sequence-formu=
las-of-arithmetic-sequence-1633103106.png" style=3D"width: 400px;"></p>
<p>The arithmetic sequence formula is given as,</p>
<ul>
<li>N<sup>th</sup> Term: a<sub>n</sub> =3D a + (n-1)d</li>
<li>S<sub>n</sub> =3D (n/2) [2a + (n - 1)d]</li>
<li>d =3D a<sub>n</sub> - a<sub>n-1</sub></li>
</ul>
<div id=3D"Nth-Term-Arithmetic-Sequence">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Nth Term of Arithmetic Sequence</h2>
</div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/algebra/nth-term-of-an-ap/">n<sup=
>th</sup> term of an arithmetic sequence</a> a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2</sub>, =
a<sub>3</sub>, ... is given by <strong>a<sub>n</sub> =3D a</strong><sub>1</=
sub><strong> + (n - 1) d</strong>. This is also known as the general term o=
f the arithmetic sequence. This directly follows from the understanding tha=
t the arithmetic sequence a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2</sub>, a<sub>3</sub>, ... =
=3D a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>1</sub> + d, a<sub>1</sub> + 2d, a<sub>1</sub> + 3=
d,... The following table shows some arithmetic sequences along with the fi=
rst term, the common difference, and the n<sup>th</sup> term.</p>
<table border=3D"1">
<thead>
<tr>
<th scope=3D"col">Arithmetic Sequence</th>
<th scope=3D"col">First Term<br>
			(a)</th>
<th scope=3D"col">Common Difference<br>
			(d)</th>
<th scope=3D"col">
<p>n<sup>th</sup> term<br>
<strong>a<sub>n</sub> =3D a</strong><sub>1</sub><strong> + (n - 1) d</stron=
g></p>
</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
</tbody>
<tbody>
</tbody>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>80, 75, 70, 65, 60, ...</td>
<td>80</td>
<td>-5</td>
<td>80 + (n - 1) (-5)<br>
			=3D -5n + 85</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>=CF=80/2, =CF=80, 3=CF=80/2, 2=CF=80, ....</td>
<td>=CF=80/2</td>
<td>=CF=80/2</td>
<td>=CF=80/2 + (n - 1) (=CF=80/2)<br>
			=3D n=CF=80/2</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
<p>-=E2=88=9A2, -2=E2=88=9A2, -3=E2=88=9A2, -4=E2=88=9A2, ...</p>
</td>
<td>-=E2=88=9A2</td>
<td>-=E2=88=9A2</td>
<td>-=E2=88=9A2 + (n - 1) (-=E2=88=9A2)<br>
			=3D -=E2=88=9A2 n</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>Arithmetic Sequence Recursive Formula</h3>
<p>The above formula for finding the n<sup>t</sup><sup>h </sup>term of an a=
rithmetic sequence is used to find any term of the sequence when the values=
 of 'a<sub>1</sub>' and 'd' are known. There is another formula to find the=
 n<sup>th</sup> term which is called the "<a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.co=
m/arithmetic-sequence-recursive-formula/">recursive formula of an arithmeti=
c sequence</a>" and is used to find a term (a<sub>n</sub>) of the sequence =
when its previous term (a<sub>n-1</sub>) and 'd' are known. It says</p>
<p><strong>a<sub>n</sub> =3D a<sub>n-1</sub> + d</strong></p>
<p>This formula just follows the definition of the arithmetic sequence.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Find a<sub>21</sub> of an arithmetic sequence =
if a<sub>19</sub> =3D -72 and d =3D 7.</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>By using the recursive formula,</p>
<p>a<sub>20</sub> =3D a<sub>19</sub> + d =3D -72 + 7 =3D -65</p>
<p>a<sub>21</sub> =3D a<sub>20</sub> + d =3D -65 + 7 =3D -58</p>
<p>Therefore, a<sub>21</sub> =3D -58.</p>
<div id=3D"Sum-Arithmetic-Sequence">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Arithmetic Series</h2>
</div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/algebra/Sum-of-arithmetic-sequenc=
e/">sum of the arithmetic sequence formula</a> is used to find the sum of i=
ts first n terms. Note that the sum of terms of an arithmetic sequence is k=
nown as arithmetic series. Consider an arithmetic series in which the first=
 term is a<sub>1</sub> (or 'a') and the common difference is d. The sum of =
its first n terms is denoted by S<sub>n</sub>. Then</p>
<ul>
<li>When the n<sup>th</sup> term is NOT known: S<sub>n</sub>=3D n/2 [2a<sub=
>1</sub> + (n-1) d]</li>
<li>When the n<sup>th</sup> term is known: S<sub>n</sub> =3D n/2 [a<sub>1</=
sub> + a<sub>n</sub>]</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example</strong></p>
<p>Ms. Natalie earns $200,000 per annum and her salary increases by $25,000=
 per annum. Then how much does she earn at the end of the first 5 years?</p=
>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>The amount earned by Ms. Natalie for the first year is, a =3D 2,00,000. =
The increment per annum is, d =3D 25,000. We have to calculate her earnings=
 in the first 5 years. Hence n =3D 5. Substituting these values in the sum =
sum of arithmetic sequence formula,</p>
<p>S<sub>n</sub>=3D n/2 [2a<sub>1</sub> + (n-1) d]</p>
<p>=E2=87=92 S<sub>n</sub> =3D 5/2(2(200000) + (5 - 1)(25000))</p>
<p>=3D 5/2 (400000 +100000)</p>
<p>=3D 5/2 (500000)</p>
<p>=3D 1250000</p>
<p>She earns $1,250,000 in 5 years. We can use this formula to be more help=
ful for larger values of 'n'.</p>
<h3>Sum of Arithmetic Sequence</h3>
<p>Let us take an arithmetic sequence that has its first term to be a<sub>1=
</sub> and the common difference to be d. Then the sum of the first 'n' ter=
ms of the sequence is given by</p>
<p>S<sub>n</sub> =3D a<sub>1</sub> + (a<sub>1</sub> + d) + (a<sub>1</sub> +=
 2d) + =E2=80=A6 + a<sub>n</sub> ... (1)</p>
<p>Let us write the same sum from right to left (i.e., from the n<sup>th</s=
up> term to the first term).</p>
<p>S<sub>n</sub> =3D a<sub>n</sub> + (a<sub>n</sub> =E2=80=93 d) + (a<sub>n=
</sub> =E2=80=93 2d) + =E2=80=A6 + a<sub>1</sub> ... (2)</p>
<p>Adding (1) and (2), all terms with 'd' get canceled.</p>
<p>2S<sub>n</sub> =3D (a<sub>1</sub> + a<sub>n</sub>) + (a<sub>1</sub> + a<=
sub>n</sub>) + (a<sub>1</sub> + a<sub>n</sub>) + =E2=80=A6 + (a<sub>1</sub>=
 + a<sub>n</sub>)</p>
<p>2S<sub>n</sub> =3D n (a<sub>1</sub> + a<sub>n</sub>)</p>
<p><strong>S<sub>n</sub> =3D [n(a<sub>1</sub> + a<sub>n</sub>)]/2</strong><=
/p>
<p>By substituting a<sub>n</sub> =3D a<sub>1</sub> + (n =E2=80=93 1)d into =
the last formula, we have</p>
<p>S<sub>n</sub> =3D n/2 [a<sub>1</sub> + a<sub>1</sub> + (n =E2=80=93 1)d]=
 (or)</p>
<p><strong>S<sub>n</sub> =3D n/2 [2a<sub>1</sub> + (n =E2=80=93 1)d]</stron=
g></p>
<p>Thus, we have derived both formulas for the sum of the arithmetic sequen=
ce.</p>
<div id=3D"Difference-Arithmetic-Sequence-Geometric-Difference">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Difference Between Arithmetic Sequence and Geometric Sequence</h2>
</div>
<p>Here are the differences between arithmetic and <a href=3D"https://www.c=
uemath.com/algebra/what-are-geometric-progressions/">geometric sequence</a>=
:</p>
<table border=3D"1">
<thead>
<tr>
<th scope=3D"col"><strong>Arithmetic Sequence</strong></th>
<th scope=3D"col"><strong>Geometric Sequence</strong></th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
</tbody>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>In this, the differences between every two consecutive numbers are the =
same.</td>
<td>In this, the <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/commercial-math/ratio/"=
>ratios</a> of every two consecutive numbers are the same.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>It is identified by the first term (a) and the common difference (d).</=
td>
<td>It is identified by the first term (a) and the <a href=3D"https://www.c=
uemath.com/common-ratio-formula/">common ratio</a> (r).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>There is a linear relationship between the terms.</td>
<td>There is an <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/calculus/exponential-fun=
ctions/">exponential relationship</a> between the terms.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Important Notes on Arithmetic Sequence:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>In arithmetic sequences, the difference between every two successive nu=
mbers is the same.</li>
<li>The common difference of an arithmetic sequence a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2<=
/sub>, a<sub>3</sub>, ... is, d =3D a<sub>2</sub> - a<sub>1</sub> =3D a<sub=
>3</sub> - a<sub>2</sub> =3D ...</li>
<li>The n<sup>th</sup> term of an arithmetic sequence is a<sub>n</sub> =3D =
a<sub>1</sub> + (n=E2=88=921)d.</li>
<li>The sum of the first n terms of an arithmetic sequence is S<sub>n</sub>=
 =3D n/2[2a<sub>1</sub> + (n =E2=88=92 1)d].</li>
<li>The common difference between arithmetic sequences can be either positi=
ve or negative or zero.</li>
</ul>
